      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">Component 3 (T/T) of the Landscape Reading locks today — OPVL on your 3 sources.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Component 3 — OPVL on 3 sources (one must be your AI source)</div>
    <p>Full OPVL — Origin, Purpose, Value, Limitation — on <strong>all three</strong> of your sources, one of which <em>must be</em> the AI source you used. The Limitation has to be <strong>specific</strong> (survey date, spatial resolution, contested interpretation, missing variables). Generic Limitations like "it's not the most recent source" — or "AI can hallucinate" on the AI source — don't clear the T/T bar. This is <strong>a T/T component and it locks today</strong>; the band becomes part of your overall T/T mark.</p>
    {% set submit = { id: "u2-b7", text: "Submit via Google Classroom" } %}{% include "partials/submit-link.njk" %}
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> OPVL specificity is a T/T thread for the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a>. The rubric calls out "<em>OPVL applied to 3 sources including the AI source; at least one Limitation is specific and substantive</em>" as T/T 7-8. This is the third lock in the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">rolling-summative</a> sequence. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
